sec.p:
We prove that in a heterogeneous‐belief market with an infinite number of investors,
               \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $K\rightarrow \infty $ \end{document}
            , and an infinite number of risky assets,
               \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $n\rightarrow \infty $ \end{document}
            , the CAPM risk‐return relationship precisely holds. Moreover, despite the fact that investors hold variousinefficientportfolios locatedbelowthe capital market line (CML) (hence the investors’ expected utility decreases) and the two‐fund separation theorem doesnothold, the CAPM risk‐return relationship remains intact. When the number of assets is finite, there is a systematic pricing bias in the heterogeneous market relative to the CAPM pricing. However, whenKandnare finite but reasonably large, we show by numerical simulations that the CAPM holds almost precisely. Hence, the fact that we empirically observe various investors holding different risky portfolios does not contradict the CAPM risk‐return relationship, which should hold in large markets even in the case of heterogeneous beliefs.

The paper is structured as follows.Section IIreviews the related literature.Section IIIprovides a description of the model. InSection IVwe present our main theoretical result, stating that when the number of assets and the number of investors approach infinity, the pricing in the heterogeneous market converges to the CAPM pricing, and the CAPM risk‐return relationship is restored, despite the fact that investors’ opinions are very diverse and that they select inefficient portfolios located below the CML. This result assumes an infinite market (
               \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $K\rightarrow \infty $ \end{document}
            ,
               \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $n\rightarrow \infty $ \end{document}
            ). However, inSection Vwe employ numerical simulations to show that it suffices to have a modest number of investors (
               \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $K=10,000$ \end{document}
            ) and assets (
               \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $n=20$ \end{document}
            ) for the CAPM risk‐return relationship to hold almost perfectly, even with a relatively large degree of heterogeneity. Concluding remarks are given inSection VI.

In two comprehensive studies, Admati (1985) and Biais et al. (2003) analyze equilibrium pricing with heterogeneous information, joint normal distributions, and constant absolute risk aversion (CARA) preferences. Admati assumes that investors observe private signals, and she shows that if the supplies of the risky assets are known, prices are fully revealing. Thus all investors hold the market portfolio, and the CAPM holds. Biais et al. employ a similar framework, but with much less restrictive assumptions; they assume that the supplies are not known, which implies that the structure of the market portfolio is not known to investors, in line with Roll’s (1977) critique. Biais et al. assume that investors have different signals but have identical precision. Thus there is agreement on the variance‐covariance matrix. They also assume normal distributions and CARA preferences. They show that in this framework, an equilibrium that is similar to the CAPM equilibrium is intact. The same CAPM equilibrium prices are obtained as in a representative‐agent economy. Yet, they show that each investor holds a portfolio that deviates from the market portfolio because of the different private signals. Thus, though the two‐fund separation does not hold, the representative agent CAPM pricing does hold. With this respect we obtain in the present study similar results: two‐fund separation does not hold, yet the CAPM pricing is intact. Thus, in Admati (1985), prices are fully revealing; in Biais et al. (2003) prices are partially revealing, and in our model (as in Lintner [1969]) prices reveal no information. Our model assumes joint normality and risk aversion but does not assume CARA preferences. The cost of relaxing the assumption on preferences and the informativeness of prices is that we need to assume that the number of assets
               \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $n\rightarrow \infty $ \end{document}
            to obtain the CAPM. However, as the numerical analysis inSection Vshows, we obtain the CAPM almost precisely even for a relatively small number of assets.

In the CAPM an equilibrium relationship between expected returns and risk is derived. To show the effect of heterogeneous beliefs on equilibrium prices and on the risk‐return relationship, we first discuss the equilibrium price determination under homogeneous beliefs. Then, in subsectionBwe turn to heterogeneous beliefs. In the homogeneous‐beliefs case, we employ Sharpe’s approach, which assumes that the mean rate of return vector, \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} 
