We numerically investigate by simulation two market sizes: a market with
               \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $n=5$ \end{document}
            stocks and a market with
               \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $n=20$ \end{document}
            stocks. We takeKto vary between 100 and 10,000. We first discuss simulations of markets with uncorrelated assets and then report the results for the case of correlated assets.

So far, for the sake of simplicity, we have assumed uncorrelated assets. We now turn to the numerical simulation for the correlated case. We would like to mention at the outset that with relatively high correlations the homogeneous CAPM may not hold, because it has been shown empirically that high correlations and a large number of assets typically lead to many short positions in the tangency portfolio, which is in contradiction to homogeneous expectations equilibrium (see, e.g., Levy1983). However, theoretically, the CAPM does not rule out the case of high correlations. Lintner (1965a, 598) argues that asset prices will “adjust and readjust” until market clearance and the CAPM equilibrium will be obtained simultaneously. In other words, it is possible that the ex post estimates of the parameters differ significantly from the ex ante parameters, and we may have short positions with ex post data, but not with ex ante data. As this issue is not the focus of the present study, we handle the correlated asset case in two ways: first, we consider the case of a rather sparse correlation matrix, such that all the positions in the tangency portfolio are positive; hence the homogeneous CAPM equilibrium is valid. Second, we employ empirical estimates of the means and covariances, which yields relatively high correlations.15In this case the tangency portfolio may involve short positions. In order to find the relationship between the homogeneous and heterogeneous optimum investment proportions, we run the regression

               where
                  \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $x^{*}_{i}$ \end{document}
               is the aggregate investment proportion in the heterogeneous expectations model, and
